Patch: preload all undistorted images into a RAM cache in gsplat's
examples/datasets/colmap.py Dataset class.

Why
---
The vanilla simple_trainer Dataset re-reads each image from disk and
re-runs cv2.remap() on every training iteration. With 185 full-res
Mip-NeRF 360 images that's the dominant per-iter cost on an A100 — GPU
util sits at ~50% bouncing 0..80% because the data pipeline starves it.

What
----
1. In `Dataset.__init__`: after computing `self.indices`, walk every
   index, decode the JPEG, run undistortion+ROI crop *once*, and store
   the resulting numpy array in `self._image_cache`.
2. In `Dataset.__getitem__`: read from `self._image_cache[index]`
   instead of touching disk or cv2.remap. The cache stores
   already-undistorted images so the per-iter undistort branch is gone.

Memory cost
-----------
- garden train split: 161 images → 8.42 GB RAM
- garden val split:    24 images → 1.26 GB RAM
- The server has 629 GB RAM available, so this is free.

Speed impact (garden, A100 PCIe 40GB)
-------------------------------------
- Before: ~6.7 it/s (data pipeline bound, GPU often idle)
- After:  ~12.2 it/s (1.8x), GPU util 0..83% bouncing — still room

How to apply on the server
--------------------------
The patch script `patch_colmap.py` (uploaded via scp to
/root/autodl-tmp/patch_colmap.py on the AutoDL box) is idempotent — it
checks for `_image_cache` in the file and skips if already patched, and
saves a backup to `colmap.py.pre_cache_bak`.

